DIV1.P:
This Discourse was so lively, so much to the Purpose, and touched
them all so sensibly, that it was ea∣sily seen, even in the very Countenan∣ces of the whole Body, that it was very agreeable to them: and fre∣quently, upon his offering to stop, they cryed, Go on, my Lord, Pray go on, my Lord. He answer'd, Pray, my Lords, let some Body give their Opinions as well as I; says one that sat right against him, you speak all our Opinions, we entreat you to go on, my Lord; upon these Pressings, he continued his Dis∣course, and “told them, one of the great Mischiefs these Tumults and this Rebellion, for such he said it was to them, as well as to the Govern∣ment, had brought upon them, were the repealing the Triennial Bill, for as for that of suspending the Habeas Corpus Act, though it fell heavy upon some of their Friends, yet he told them they could not blame the Court for taking that Step, and that it was nothing but what every Government had done in their Turn, and would, and ought to do again upon such Occasions; and being temporary, would influ∣ence Matters but a little while;
But this cursed Septennial Law, said he, your Lordships are sensible has ruined us all; Before that, he told them, they had some View of retrie∣ving the Mischiefs which the wrong Steps of the Rebellion and Rabbling had brought upon them; and tho' they had lost some Friends, and ma∣ny had brought themselves into such Circumstances, as they could not own them without manifest Dan∣ger, yet they had cultivated the general Disaffection to such a De∣gree, that upon a new Election of Parliament, they made no doubt to have given a new Turn to the Gentlemen at Court, and to have let his Majesty see, THAT the Inte∣rest of the Church did not lye where some People had placed it: THAT the High-Party were not so despicable an Interest as they had been represented: THAT it was not safe to slight them, as some Men would have them slight∣ed: and in a Word, THAT it was his Interest to shift Hands in the Ad∣ministration, if he would effectually regain the Affection of his Subjects.”
